title: Refrigerator won't turn on when plugged in

full_content.content: Refrigerator won't turn on when plugged in
Common reasons your Refrigerator won't turn on when plugged in
The most common reasons your refrigerator won’t turn on when plugged in are a defective electronic control board, faulty thermostat or damaged power cord.
We can help! Our service technicians have repaired over 120,000 refrigerators. We can fix yours no matter where you bought it.
Most common repairs needed to fix a  refrigerator

When your refrigerator won’t turn on when plugged in, a failed electronic control board can be causing the problem. The electronic control board acts as the refrigerator's central control system, managing critical functions such as temperature regulation, fan operation, defrost cycles, icemaker functionality, and dispenser operations. When the board malfunctions, it can keep the refrigerator from turning on when you plug in the power cord. It's best to have a Sears Home Services professional conduct diagnostic tests on the board to determine if replacement is warranted. If the control board is preventing the refrigerator from powering up, the technician will replace the electronic control board.
How to replace an electronic control board on the back of a refrigerator

When your refrigerator has a dial control and an electro-mechanical temperature control thermostat, a failed electrical contact in that thermostat can prevent the refrigerator from turning on when plugged in. The power cord wires connect to the temperature control thermostat to provide power to the fridge. When the power cord is properly supplying power to the fridge through the temperature control thermostat but the refrigerator will not turn on, you’ll likely need to have a service technician replace the temperature control thermostat.
How to replace a refrigerator temperature control thermostat

When the refrigerator won’t turn on when plugged in, a faulty power cord may be causing the failure. The power cord connects to the electronic control board or the temperature control thermostat depending on the type of fridge that you have. Damage to the internal wiring or the power cord prongs will prevent electric current from traveling through the power cord to turn on the refrigerator. Have a service technician examine the power cord for your refrigerator and replace that part if it’s broken or damaged.
What to expect when you experience a refrigerator that won’t turn on when plugged in
Steps to resolve a problem with your refrigerator that won’t turn on when plugged in

Solving most problems with a refrigerator that won’t turn on when plugged in usually involves replacing a defective electronic control board, faulty thermostat or broken power cord. However, there are many potential causes for this problem. A tripped circuit breaker or bad refrigerator electrical outlet can also prevent the fridge from turning on when plugged in. A thorough diagnosis is key to understanding the extent of repairs needed and what’s needed for resolving the power issue.
Our recommendations for a refrigerator that won’t turn on when plugged in

When the refrigerator has no power it can be for many reasons. Checking the house circuit breaker and electrical outlet for power are the first steps to resolve a power problem with the fridge. If the failure is internal, avoid replacing unneeded parts by having a Sears Home Services professional inspect the refrigerator and repair the problem. Our technicians are experienced at diagnosing all types of refrigerator failures.
What to watch for with a refrigerator that won’t turn on when you plug it in

Effectively diagnosing malfunctions in modern appliances necessitates a comprehensive understanding and specialized training. Addressing refrigerator issues without employing precise diagnostic techniques may lead to ineffective repairs and unnecessary part replacements. With significant advancements in appliance technology over the past decade, contemporary refrigerator models now feature intricate electronic components that pose considerable challenges for troubleshooting. Consequently, do-it-yourself repairs on modern appliances have become increasingly more complicated. Schedule refrigerator repair service to have a Sears Home Services technician visit your home and fix a power problem in your fridge.

full_content.content: Why won’t my refrigerator turn on when plugged in?
Check the power supply, circuit breaker, and power cord for faults.
Could a damaged power cord prevent my refrigerator from turning on?
Yes, if the power cord is damaged, it can stop the refrigerator from receiving power.
How do I fix a refrigerator that won’t turn on when plugged in?
Inspect the power supply, cord, and circuit breaker for issues. Replace any damaged components.
What causes a refrigerator to not turn on even when plugged in?
A faulty power cord, tripped circuit breaker, or issue with the internal wiring can prevent it from powering on.

full_content.content: How Does a Refrigerator Ice Maker Work?
Learn how a refrigerator ice maker works and how to keep it in top shape.

A compressor is a mechanical device that increases the pressure of a gas by reducing its volume, essential in various systems including refrigerators, air conditioners, and HVAC units for cooling and refrigeration processes.
A condenser is a component of HVAC and refrigeration systems, responsible for releasing absorbed heat from the refrigerant into the outside air or a water line, thus facilitating the cooling process.
What is a Dual Ice Maker?

A dual ice maker is a feature in some refrigerators that includes two separate ice makers: one in the fridge compartment and another in the freezer section. This setup doubles the appliance's ice-making capacity.

A French-door refrigerator features two doors that open side-by-side on the top section for the refrigerator compartment, with a bottom freezer drawer, combining style, efficiency, and easy access to both refrigerated and frozen goods.
